These posts are using a distract tactic because they are discussing a completely irrelevant topic (making fun of Bollywood actors/comedians) in the midst of a coordinated campaign about Dubai Police's humanitarian efforts. The posts are not related to international relations or the main topic of the campaign, thus serving as a distraction from the main message.

column13:
The following post uses an Excite tactic: 
@JayGenXer LMFAO. So hypocritical. The CPC avoided nearly all media under Harper.

This post elicits a positive emotion of amusement by using humor to point out hypocrisy, which can be exciting for the reader.

column17:
The following post uses a distract tactic:
@TDotResident @Fordnation is Corrupt AF and needs to be investigated and arrested. Racketeering Ontario's public assets, land and insider trading for his pay to play pals! @rcmpgrcpolice #EnoughisEnough #generalstrike #FordisCorrupt #russianasset #fact

This post is focusing on allegations of corruption against Fordnation, which is not relevant to the initial topic of international relations and foreign interference. The distract tactic is used to shift the focus away from the original discussion about the Fraser Institute and foreign interference in Canadian politics.

The post by @LindseySnell and @Spriter99880 both use a distract tactic by bringing up an unrelated topic to the conversation about international relations and the situation in Artsakh. 

@LindseySnell says, "Aliyev, Europe’s reliable fascist, sorry 'reliable partner'" which is unrelated to the discussion at hand and serves as a distraction.

@Spriter99880 says, "🤣🤣🤣 couldn’t have happened to a nicer person. The reliable partner of Aliyev" which similarly brings up an irrelevant topic and tries to divert attention away from the main issue being discussed.

These posts use the distract tactic by introducing unrelated topics into the conversation to divert attention away from the serious issue being discussed.
